title: Dubliners
creator: James Joyce
source: Librivox recording of a public-domain text
description: LibriVox recording of Dubliners, by James Joyce. Read by Tadhg Hynes. Dubliners is a collection of 15 short stories by James Joyce, first published in 1914. They form a naturalistic depiction of Irish middle class life in and around Dublin in the early years of the 20th century. The stories were written when Irish nationalism was at its peak and a search for a national identity and purpose was raging; at a crossroads of history and culture, Ireland was jolted by various converging ideas and influences. They centre on Joyce's idea of an epiphany: a moment where a character experiences self-understanding or illumination. Many of the characters in Dubliners later appear in minor roles in Joyce's novel Ulysses. The initial stories in the collection are narrated by child protagonists, and as the stories continue, they deal with the lives and concerns of progressively older people. This is in line with Joyce's tripartite division of the collection into childhood, adolescence, and maturity. (Summary from Wikipedia) For further information, including links to online text, reader information, RSS feeds, CD cover or other formats (if available), please go to the LibriVox catalog page for this recording. For more free audio books or to become a volunteer reader, visit LibriVox.org. Download M4B (182MB)
subject: Joyce; Dublin; the dead; Trinity College; Ireland; short stories; literature; Librivox; audiobook

reviews.reviewbody: It's so refreshing to hear James Joyce in an authentic Dublin accent. Thanks for voluntering - I hope you'll attempt Portrait and Ulysses!
I must agree with the first reviewer; the reader's Irish accent really makes the audiobook even more wonderful to listen to. Seemingly rofessionally performed too.
